To implement robust error handling in Express, follow these best practices:

1. **Use an Error-Handling Middleware**:
Define a middleware function with four arguments `(err, req, res, next)` at the very end of your middleware stack:
```javascript
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  const statusCode = err.statusCode || 500;
  res.status(statusCode).json({
    status: 'error',
    statusCode,
    message: err.message || 'Internal Server Error'
  });
});
```

2. **Create a Custom AppError Class**:
Inherit from the native `Error` class to support operational errors with status codes:
```javascript
class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(message, statusCode) {
    super(message);
    this.statusCode = statusCode;
    this.isOperational = true;
    Error.captureStackTrace(this, this.constructor);
  }
}
```

3. **Catch Async Errors Automatically**:
Use a wrapper function or `express-async-errors` to catch errors from async routes without repeating `try-catch` blocks:
```javascript
const catchAsync = fn => {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    fn(req, res, next).catch(next);
  };
};

app.get('/users', catchAsync(async (req, res, next) => {
  const users = await User.find();
  res.json(users);
}));
```
